LONG ISLAND SOLAR FARM, LLC
Market-Based Rate Wholesale Power Sale Tariff
1. Availability. Long Island Solar Farm, LLC ("Long Island Solar Farm") makes electric capacity, energy, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of capacity, energy, or ancillary services by Long Island Solar Farm not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Long Island Solar Farm.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between purchaser and Long Island Solar Farm.
5. Seller Category. Long Island Solar Farm is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. Section;35.36(a), in the Northeast region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. Section;35.36(a), in each of the Northwest, Southeast, Central, Southwest Power Pool, and Southwest regions.
6. Ancillary Services. Long Island Solar Farm may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
a. PJM Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 20-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
b. New York Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
c. New England Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
d. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
e. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Energy Imbalance Service, Spinning Reserves, and Supplemental Reserves. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the pubic utility affiliated with the third-party supplier; and (3) sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers.
7. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Long Island Solar Farm shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.FR. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Long Island Solar Farm has received (i) waiver of the accounting and periodic reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, except for Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart B and C, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities and the assumption of liabilities pursuant to Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. Section;824e, and Part 34 of the Commission's Regulations. See Long Island Solar Farm, Docket No. ER11-3589-000.
9. Effective Date: This tariff is effective on and after September 12, 2011.
10. Revisions to this Tariff: Long Island Solar Farm may file revisions to this Tariff by notifying purchasers in writing and by unilaterally making the appropriate filing with the Commission pursuant to the provisions of Section 205 of the Federal Power Act. 1

LONG ISLAND SOLAR FARM, LLC
Market-Based Rate Wholesale Power Sale Tariff
1. Availability. Long Island Solar Farm, LLC ("Long Island Solar Farm" or "Seller") makes electric capacity, energy, and ancillary services available under this Tariff to any purchaser for resale.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all sales of capacity, energy, or ancillary services by Long Island Solar Farm that are subject to the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("Commission") and not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule.
3. Rates. All sales pursuant to this Tariff shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Long Island Solar Farm.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions of sales shall be established by agreement between purchaser and Long Island Solar Farm.
5. Seller Category. Long Island Solar Farm is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. Section;35.36(a), in all regions.
6. Ancillary Services. Long Island Solar Farm may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
a. PJM Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
b. New York Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
c. New England Region: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
d. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
e. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; or (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
7. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Long Island Solar Farm shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.FR. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Long Island Solar Farm has received (i) waiver of the accounting and periodic reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, except for Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart B and C, except for Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities and the assumption of liabilities pursuant to Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. Section;824e, and Part 34 of the Commission's Regulations. See Long Island Solar Farm, Docket No. ER11-3589-000.
9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective upon the date authorized by the Commission.
